<subsection xml:id="ss_open_mapping">
<title>Open mapping theorem</title>


<definition xml:id="d_open_map">
<title>Open mapping</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>f</m> be a complex function with open domain <m>D</m>. We say <m>f</m> is <term>open</term> if for all open sets <m>U\subseteq D</m>, <m>f(U)</m> is open: <ie/>, <m>f</m> maps open sets to open sets. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<lemma xml:id="lem_open_mapping">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>f</m> be a complex function with open domain <m>D</m>. The following statements are equivalent. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>f</m> is open.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        For all open subsets <m>U\subseteq D</m> and all <m>z_0\in U</m> there is an open ball <m>B_r(z_0)\subseteq U</m> such that <m>f(B_r(z_0))</m> is open. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            We prove both implications separately. 
        </p>
        <p>
            Assume <m>f</m> is open, let <m>U</m> be an open subset of <m>D</m>, and let <m>z_0\in U</m>. Since <m>U</m> is open, we have <m>B_r(z_0)\subseteq U</m> for some <m>r&gt; 0</m>. Since <m>f</m> is open, <m>f(B_r(z_0))</m> is open.  
        </p>
        <p>
            Now assume (2) holds, and let <m>U</m> be an open subset of <m>D</m>. Given any <m>w_0\in f(U)</m>, we have <m>w_0=f(z_0)</m> for some <m>z_0\in V</m>. By condition (2), there is an open ball <m>B_r(z_0)\subseteq U</m> such that <m>V=f(B_r(z_0))</m> is open. Since <m>w_0\in f(B_r(z_0))\subseteq f(U)</m>, we have shown that for all <m>w_0\in f(U)</m> there is an open set <m>V</m> such that <m>w_0\in V\subseteq f(U)</m>. It follows that <m>f(U)</m> is open. 
        </p>
    </proof>
</lemma>
<theorem xml:id="th_locally_m_to_one">
<title>Locally <m>m</m>-to-one</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>f</m> be a nonconstant analytic function with open domain <m>D</m>. Fix any open subset <m>U\subseteq D</m> and <m>z_0\in U</m>. Let <m>w_0=f(z_0)</m>, let <m>h(z)=f(z)-w_0</m>, and let <m>m</m> be the order of <m>z_0</m> as a zero of the function <m>f(z)-w_0</m>. There is an open ball <m>B_r(z_0)\subseteq U</m> satisfying the following properties. 
 <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        For all <m>z\in B_r(z_0)-\{z_0\}</m>, <m>f(z)\ne w_0</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        For all <m>w\ne w_0\in f(B_r(z_0))</m>, the function <m>h(z)=f(z)-w</m> has <m>m</m> distinct zeros in <m>B_r(z_0)</m>, each of order one. In particular, <m>f</m> is an <m>m</m>-to-<m>1</m> function when restricted to punctured open ball <m>B_r(z_0)-\{z_0\}</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>f(B_r(z_0))</m> is open. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>

<theorem xml:id="th_open_mapping">
<title>Open mapping theorem</title>
<statement>
<p>
If <m>f</m> is nonconstant and analytic on an open connected domain <m>D</m>, then <m>f</m> is open. 
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
This follows from (3) of <xref ref="th_locally_m_to_one"/> and <xref ref="lem_open_mapping"/>. 
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>
<corollary xml:id="cor_max_min_modulus">
    <title>Maximum/minimum modulus theorem</title>    
    <statement>
        <p>
            Assume <m>U</m> is open and connected, and that <m>f</m> is analytic and nonconstant on <m>U</m>. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <title>Maximum modulus principle</title>
                    <p>
                       <m>\abs{f}</m> does not have a local maximum value on <m>U</m>.  
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Minimum modulus principle</title>
                    <p>
                        <m>\abs{f}</m> does not have a positive local minimum value on <m>U</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Complex extreme value theorem</title>
                    <p>
                        Let <m>K</m> be a closed and bounded subset of <m>U</m>. The maximum value of <m>\abs{f}</m> is attained only on the boundary <m>\partial K</m> of <m>K</m>. The minimum value of <m>\abs{f}</m> on <m>K</m> is either <m>0</m>, or is attained on the boundary <m>\partial K</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
</corollary>
<corollary xml:id="cor_schwarzs_lemma">
    <title>Schwarz's lemma</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If <m>f</m> is analytic on <m>B_1(0)</m> and satisfies <m>f(0)=0</m> and <m>\abs{f(z)}\leq 1</m> for all <m>z\in B_1(0)</m>, then <m>\abs{f(z)}\leq \abs{z}</m> for all <m>z\in B_1(0)</m>, and <m>\abs{f'(0)}\leq 1</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
            Furthermore, if <m>\abs{f(z)}=\abs{z}</m> for some <m>z\in B_1(0)</m>, or if <m>\abs{f'(z_0)}=1</m>, then <m>f(z)=e^{i\alpha}z</m> for some <m>z\in </m>: <ie/>, <m>f</m> is the rotation by <m>\alpha</m> transformation in this case. 
            </p>
    </statement>
</corollary>

<theorem xml:id="th_inv_fun">
<title>Inverse function theorem</title>
<statement>
<p>
Assume <m>f</m> is analytic at <m>z_0</m> and that <m>f'(z_0)\ne 0</m>. There is an open ball <m>B=B_r(z_0)</m> satisfying the following properties. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
           Let <m>V=f(B_r(z_0))</m>. The function <m>f\colon B_r(z_0)\rightarrow V</m> is bijective. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            The inverse map <m>f^{-1}\colon V\rightarrow B_r(z_0)</m> is analytic and satisfies
            <md>
                <mrow>(f^{-1})'(w) \amp = \frac{1}{f'(f^{-1}(w))} </mrow>
            </md>
            for all <m>w\in U</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            For all <m>w\in V</m> we have 
            <men>
             f^{-1}(w)  =\frac{1}{2\pi i}\int_{\gamma}\frac{zf'(z)}{f(z)-w}\, dz, \ \gamma(t)=z_0+re^{it}, t\in [0,2\pi]
            </men>.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>


